Which flat type offers the most favorable investment opportunity for rental purposes in a specific town within a price range of 500000SGD?¶

What is the difference in the prices of flat types?¶

In [ ]:
# getting the different flat types
flat_types = np.unique(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type'])

# getting the average resale prices for each flat type
# creating an numpy array with the length of flat types
resale_prices = np.zeros(len(flat_types))
# finding average resale price of each flat type and storing them into resale_prices array
for i in range(len(flat_types)):
    resale_prices[i] = np.mean(data_resale_flat_prices['resale_price'][data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type'] == flat_types[i]])

# Plotting the graph
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
plt.bar(flat_types, resale_prices)
plt.xlabel('Flat Type',fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Average Resale Price',fontsize=15)
plt.title('Average Resale Prices Across Different Flat Types',fontsize=20)
plt.grid(color="gray",alpha=0.7)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

This is a bar chart showing the different Flat types and their prices. There are 7 flat types in this bar chart. They are 1 Room, 2 Room, 3 Room, 4 Room, 5 Room, Executie and Multi Generation.

The cheapest flat type is the 1 Room flat, which costs close to 200000SGD. The most expensive flat type is the Multi-Generation Flat, costing more than 800000SGD. As the number of rooms increases, the price of the flat increases too. The Executive, 5 Room and 4 Room flat have the same number of bedrooms, with 3 bedrooms. However, the executive flat has more floor area compared to the 5 room and 4 room flats. The Multi-Generational flat has the same floor area as a 5 room flat. However, the Multi-Generational flat has two bedrooms with attached bathrooms, and two other bedrooms. This is why the Multi-Generational flat costs the most, at around 800000SGD.

As my budget is 500000SGD, I will choose the 4 room flat.

Which flat type had the most sales?¶

In [ ]:
# sum of each flat type
count_1_room = np.sum(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type']=='1 ROOM')
count_2_room = np.sum(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type']=='2 ROOM')
count_3_room = np.sum(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type']=='3 ROOM')
count_4_room = np.sum(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type']=='4 ROOM')
count_5_room = np.sum(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type']=='5 ROOM')
count_executive = np.sum(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type']=='EXECUTIVE')
count_mg = np.sum(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type']=='MULTI-GENERATION')

# sum of 1 room, 2 room and multi-generation
count_12_and_mg = count_1_room + count_mg +count_2_room

# creating a list of the sum of each flat type
sizes = [count_3_room, count_4_room, count_5_room, count_executive, count_12_and_mg]

# creating a list of the labels
labels = np.unique(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type'])

# removing 1 room, 2 room and multi-generation from the labels
new_labels = []
for label in labels:
    if label == '1 ROOM':
        np.delete(label, np.where(label == '1 ROOM'))
    elif label == '2 ROOM':
        np.delete(label, np.where(label == '2 ROOM'))
    elif label == 'MULTI-GENERATION':
        continue
    else:
        new_labels.append(label)

# adding a new label for 1 room, 2 room and multi-generation
new_labels.append('1 ROOM + 2 ROOM + MULTI-GENERATION')

explode =(0,0.1,0,0,0)

fig1,ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,8),facecolor='white')
ax1.pie(sizes,explode=explode,shadow=True, autopct='%1.1f%%',textprops={'fontsize': 15})
plt.legend(new_labels,title="Flat Types",loc="center left" ,bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
plt.title("Distribution of Flat Types Sold",fontsize=20)
plt.show()

The pie chart below shows the breakdown of the number of flats sold in this dataset. There are a total of 7 flat types, but as the 1-room, 2-room and Multi Generation flat types had low numbers of sales, they were combined into one category.

As you can see, the 4-room flat is the most popular type, accounting for over 40% of all sales. This is likely due to its size and affordability. 4-room flats are typically large enough to accommodate a family of up to four people, while still being relatively affordable. The 5-room flat is the second most popular type, accounting for just over 25% of all sales. 5-room flats are larger than 4-room flats, and are often chosen by families with more than four children. 3-room flats are the third most popular type, accounting for just over 23% of all sales. 3-room flats are smaller than 4-room flats, but they are still a popular choice for families with two or three children. Executive flats are the fourth most popular type, accounting for just over 7% of all sales. Executive flats are larger than 4-room flats, and they often come with additional features such as private lifts and balconies. 1-room, 2-room and Multi Generation flats are the least popular type, accounting for just over 1% of all sales. These flats are typically chosen by singles, couples or small families who are looking for an affordable option.

I will be choosing the 4-room flat as they have been sold more, which means there is more options of it across different towns. This will give me a wider range of choice when it comes to finding a flat that meets my needs.

What is the relationship between the lease commence date and the resale prices of 4 room flats?¶

In [ ]:
# 4 room flat
room_4 = data_resale_flat_prices[data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type']=='4 ROOM']

lease_commence_date = np.unique(room_4['lease_commence_date'])

# getting the average resale price of each lease commence date
avg_price = []
for date in lease_commence_date:
    avg_price.append(np.mean(room_4[room_4['lease_commence_date']==date]['resale_price']))

plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
plt.plot(lease_commence_date,avg_price,marker='o',color='red')
plt.title("Average Resale Price of 4 Room Flats by Lease Commence Date",fontsize=20)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.xlabel('Lease Commence Date',fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Average Price (SGD)',fontsize=15)
plt.grid(color="gray",alpha=0.4)
plt.show()

This line graph shows the relationship between the lease commence date (LCD) and the average resale price in Singapore dollars (SGD). All HDB flats are leased for a period of 99 years, and the LCD is the starting point for this calculation. A flat with a shorter lease term will be worth less than a flat with a longer lease term.

From the graph, we can see that the average resale price started with a steep increase and then decreased. The average resale price was around 600,000 SGD and it then increased to more than 900000 SGD in a few years. The price dropped back down to 450000 SGD when the LCD was 1970. Flats with an LCD between 1970 and the mid-2000s had average resale prices between 400000 SGD and 500000 SGD.

Flats with an LCD after the mid-2000s saw their average resale price increase. Although there were a few steep drops in prices, the highest it went to was above 700000 SGD. In the mid-2010s, there was a steep increase in price, from 500000 SGD to around 700000 SGD. After that steep drop, there was an increase in the average resale price, around 700000 SGD, as the LCD was closer to 2020.

Even though a flat with a recent LCD would be worth more, there are some older flats with an LCD of before 1970 which had a resale price of above 900000 SGD. There could be several factors affecting this, including the town, flat model, and facilities in that town.

As my budget is 500000 SGD, I will be choosing a 4-room flat with an LCD between 1980 and 2000.

What is the difference between the flat models in 4 room flats?¶

In [ ]:
room_4 = data_resale_flat_prices[(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type'] == '4 ROOM') & (data_resale_flat_prices['lease_commence_date'] >= np.datetime64('1980'))& (data_resale_flat_prices['lease_commence_date'] <= np.datetime64('1990'))]
flat_types = np.unique(room_4['flat_model'])

# getting the average resale price of each flat model
average_price=[]

for flat in flat_types:
    average_price.append(np.mean(room_4[room_4['flat_model']==flat]['resale_price']))

plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
plt.bar(flat_types,average_price,color='red')
plt.title("Average prices of 4 room flats across different flat models",fontsize=20)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.xlabel('Flat Models',fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Average Resale Price (SGD)',fontsize=15)
plt.grid(color="gray",alpha=0.6)
plt.show()

This is a bar chart showing the different flat models and their average resale price. There are four different flat models for 4 room flats, and they are Improved, Model A, New Generation and Simplified.

Improved flats are the largest, with an average size of 105 square meters. They were built between 1982 and 1990 and have a refuse chute in the kitchen. Improved flats are the most expensive, with an average resale price of 600000SGD. Model A flats are similar in size to Improved flats, with an average size of 100 square meters. They were built between 1990 and 1998 and do not have a refuse chute in the kitchen. Model A flats are less expensive than Improved flats, with an average resale price of 450000SGD. New Generation flats are smaller than Improved and Model A flats, with an average size of 90 square meters. They were built between 1998 and 2004 and have a different layout, with the master bedroom located at the back of the flat. New Generation flats costs above 400000SGD. Simplified flats are the smallest of the four models, with an average size of 85 square meters. They were built after 2004 and have a different layout, with the master bedroom located at the front of the flat. Simplified flats are the least expensive of the four models, with an average resale price of around 300000SGD.

The most expensive flat model is the Improved flat model, which costs 600000SGD. The cheapest flat model is Simplified flat model, which costs below 400000SGD.

The average resale prices of flat models are positively correlated with the floor area of the flat model. This means that as the floor area of a flat model increases, so does its average resale price.

I will be choosing the Model A flat model because it is the most cost-effective option.

Info of flat models are from https://www.hdb.gov.sg/ .

Do flats in higher storeys cost more?¶

room_4 = data_resale_flat_prices[(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type'] == '4 ROOM') & (data_resale_flat_prices['lease_commence_date'] >= np.datetime64('1980'))& (data_resale_flat_prices['lease_commence_date'] <= np.datetime64('2000')) & (data_resale_flat_prices['flat_model']=='Model A')]

plt.grid(color="gray",alpha=0.6)
plt.show()

This is a bar chart showing the relationship between the storey range and the average resale price of Model A 4 room flats. As the storey range gets higher, the average resale price of the flat increases too. The highest storey range for a Model A 4 room flat is 28 to 30. A flat at this storey range costs more than 700000SGD. The cheapest flat is also the lowest storey range, floors 1 to 3, which costs just above 400000SGD.

The average resale price of the flats have been increasing as the storey range increased. However, there is an anomaly. The average resale price of a flat on storey range 19 to 21 costs close to 600000SGD. The next storey range,21 to 24 costs around 600000SGD, but it is a bit cheaper than the previous storey range. There might be several factors affecting this.

In conclusion, flats in higher storey ranges do cost more. However, there are some factors that can affect the resale price of a flat, even if it is on a higher storey range. Buyers should carefully consider all of these factors when making a decision about which flat to buy.

Based on the information in the bar chart, I would choose a Model A 4-room flat on storey range 13 to 15. This storey range has an average resale price of around 500000SGD, which is a good value for money. The flats on this storey range are also likely to have good views and plenty of natural light.

Is there a relationship between the floor area of a property and its resale price?¶

In [ ]:
room_4 = data_resale_flat_prices[(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type'] == '4 ROOM') & (data_resale_flat_prices['lease_commence_date'] >= np.datetime64('1980')) & (
    data_resale_flat_prices['lease_commence_date'] <= np.datetime64('2000')) & (data_resale_flat_prices['flat_model'] == 'Model A') & (data_resale_flat_prices['storey_range'] == '13 TO 15')]

sqm = room_4['floor_area_sqm']
resale_price = room_4['resale_price']

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
a, b = np.polyfit(sqm, resale_price, 1)
plt.scatter(sqm, resale_price)
plt.plot(sqm, a*sqm+b, color='red')
plt.title("Scatter plot of floor area vs resale price for 4 Room flats", fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel('Floor Area (sqm)', fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Resale Price (SGD)', fontsize=15)
plt.grid(color="gray", alpha=0.4)
plt.show()

The scatter plot shows the relationship between the floor area and resale price of Model A 4-room flats. There is a low positive correlation between the two variables, meaning that as the floor area increases, the resale price also tends to increase. However, there are some outliers, such as the most expensive flat which has a floor area of around 115sqm but costs close to 900000SGD.

The smallest flat has a floor area of 90 sqm and a resale price of 300000 SGD. The biggest flat has a floor area of 130 sqm but is not the most expensive flat. The most expensive flat had a floor area of around 115 sqm and costs close to 900000 SGD.Most flats have a floor area of around 100 to 110 sqm. The cheapest flat in this range costs 300000 SGD. The most expensive flat in this range costs above 800000 SGD.

In conclusion, there is a weak positive correlation between the floor area of a flat and its resale price. This means that, on average, flats with larger floor areas tend to sell for more than flats with smaller floor areas. However, there are many other factors that can affect the resale price of a flat, such as its town and facilities.

Given my budget, I will be choosing a flat with a floor area of 100 to 110 sqm. There are plenty of options available in this range.

Which town in Singapore has Model A 4-room flats with a lease commence date between 1980 and 2000, a floor area between 100 and 110sqm, and a price around 500000 SGD?¶

In [ ]:
room_4 = data_resale_flat_prices[(data_resale_flat_prices['flat_type'] == '4 ROOM') & 
                                 (data_resale_flat_prices['lease_commence_date'] >= np.datetime64('1980')) & 
                                 (data_resale_flat_prices['lease_commence_date'] <= np.datetime64('2000')) &
                                 (data_resale_flat_prices['floor_area_sqm'] >= 100) &
                                 (data_resale_flat_prices['floor_area_sqm'] <= 110) & 
                                 (data_resale_flat_prices['flat_model'] == 'Model A') & 
                                 (data_resale_flat_prices['storey_range'] == '13 TO 15')]

towns = np.unique(room_4['town'])

# getting the average resale price of each town
average_price = []

for town in towns:
    average_price.append(
        np.mean(room_4[room_4['town'] == town]['resale_price']))

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
plt.bar(towns, average_price)
plt.title("Average prices of 4 room flats across different towns", fontsize=20)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.xlabel('Towns', fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Average Resale Price (SGD)', fontsize=15)
plt.grid(color="gray", alpha=0.4)
plt.show()

This is a bar chart comparing the average resale price of a 4-room flat across different towns in Singapore. All flats considered are Model A 4-room flats, with a lease commence date between 1990 to 2000, and a floor area of 100 to 110 sqm.

From the bar chart, it is evident that the average resale prices of the same flat models vary across different towns. One possible reason for this disparity is the variation in accessibility to key areas of Singapore, such as the Central Business District (CBD). Higher-costing towns may offer better transportation, educational, and healthcare facilities.

Among the towns depicted, Queenstown emerges as the most expensive with an average resale price of approximately 800000 SGD. Central Area follows closely, with prices exceeding 700000 SGD. Conversely, the least expensive towns are Choa Chu Kang, Jurong West, Sembawang, Woodlands, and Yishun, with average prices hovering around 400000 SGD.

The price gap between the cheapest and most expensive town amounts to approximately 400000 SGD. Notably, the more expensive towns are situated closer to the center of Singapore, while the less expensive towns are located farther away.

Considering my budget of 500,000 SGD, I have shortlisted the following towns that fall within my price range: Bedok, Serangoon, and Jurong East.

Insights from the resale flat prices dataset.¶

This dataset reveals the various factors that impact the resale price of a flat in Singapore. These factors encompass the flat type, flat model, lease commence date, floor area, storey range, and town.

Diverse flat types exhibit varying price points, with higher average resale prices correlating with an increase in the number of rooms and floor area. Prospective buyers are advised to determine their desired flat type by considering the number of bedrooms they require and how they intend to allocate the floor area. Among the available options, the 4-room flats offer an optimal choice as they feature 3 bedrooms and are more affordable compared to other types of flats.

Every flat in Singapore possesses a lease commence date since HDB flats are leased for a period of 99 years. Upon the expiration of this lease, owners are required to return their property to the Housing Development Board (HDB). Consequently, the older the lease commence date, the lower the average resale price tends to be. Buyers who plan to pass on their property ownership to their children are advised to purchase flats with more recent lease commence dates. Conversely, buyers seeking short-term residency (e.g., 10 years) may consider older flats as they are typically more cost-effective.

Within each flat type, there exists a range of flat models. Specifically, for 4-room flats, four distinct models are available: Improved, Model A, New Generation, and Simplified.

Improved flats boast the largest average size of 105 square meters and were constructed between 1982 and 1990. Notably, they feature a refuse chute in the kitchen. Model A flats share a similar size with Improved flats, averaging at 100 square meters. Constructed between 1990 and 1998, these flats lack a refuse chute in the kitchen. New Generation flats are smaller than both Improved and Model A flats, with an average size of 90 square meters. Built between 1998 and 2004, these flats possess a different layout, with the master bedroom situated at the back of the unit. Simplified flats represent the smallest among the four models, averaging at 85 square meters. Constructed after 2004, these flats feature a distinct layout with the master bedroom located at the front of the unit.

Buyers can select a flat model based on their specific requirements and preferred house layout. The Simplified flat model stands as the most affordable option, while the Improved flat model commands the highest price.

Flats situated on higher storeys generally come at a higher cost, given their superior views and increased natural elevation. Buyers who do not prioritize this aspect have the option of acquiring a flat on a lower storey, which would be more economical. However, those seeking enhanced views may opt to purchase a flat on a higher storey, albeit at a higher price point.

Most 4-room Model A flats exhibit a floor area ranging from 100 to 110 square meters, resulting in varying resale prices. Within this floor area range, the least expensive flat is priced at 300,000 SGD, while the most expensive one reaches 900,000 SGD. Outliers can be observed, such as a flat with a floor area of 130 square meters, which costs around 500,000 SGD.

The selection of a town holds significant importance when purchasing a flat, with certain towns offering greater accessibility to the airport, Central Business District (CBD), educational institutions, and healthcare facilities. Buyers seeking to minimize travel time may consider acquiring a flat in prime areas such as Queenstown and Bukit Timah, with prices ranging from 700,000 to 800,000 SGD. Alternatively, those willing to trade off travel time for affordability can explore flats in Choa Chu Kang, Jurong West, Sembawang, Woodlands, and Yishun, which are priced at approximately 400,000 SGD.

This dataset demonstrates the abundance of options available for prospective buyers, thereby facilitating their decision-making process when selecting a flat that fulfills their requirements.

As for my personal situation, I have a budget of 500,000 SGD. Consequently, I intend to pursue a 4-room Model A flat with a lease commence date falling between 1990 and 2000, featuring a floor area ranging from 100 to 110 square meters. Ideally, this flat should be located in one of the following towns: Bedok, Serangoon, or Jurong East.

data_median_rent['town'] = np.char.strip(data_median_rent['town'])

towns=["BEDOK","SERANGOON","JURONG EAST"]

cheapest_towns=[]

for town in towns:
    cheapest_towns.append(np.unique(data_median_rent[data_median_rent['town']==town]['town']))

#chatgpt Extract the town names from the numpy arrays
cheapest_towns = [town[0] for town in cheapest_towns]

median_rent_of_town = []

for town in cheapest_towns:
    median_rent_of_town.append(data_median_rent[data_median_rent['town']==town]['median_rent'])

#chatgpt Remove the -1 values from the arrays
median_rent_of_town = [rent[rent != -1] for rent in median_rent_of_town]

# creating boxplot

#setting figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))

#make lines of boxplot thicker
boxprops = dict(linewidth=2)

#plotting the boxplot
bp = plt.boxplot(median_rent_of_town, labels=cheapest_towns, boxprops=boxprops)

#title, xlables, ylabels, and grid
plt.title("Spread of Median Rent of 4 Room Flats in Cheapest Towns", fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel('Towns', fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Median Rent (SGD)', fontsize=15)
plt.ylim(0, 3500)
plt.grid(color="lightgray", linestyle='--')

# Add labels for minimum and maximum values
#loops through each box in the boxplot
for i, box in enumerate(bp['boxes']):

    # Get the coordinates of the box and whiskers
    #x coordinates
    x = box.get_xdata()
    #y coordinates
    y = box.get_ydata()

    # gets whiskers  
    whiskers = bp['whiskers']

    # to get the x coordinates for each whisker
    whisker_x = [whiskers[i*2].get_xdata()[1], whiskers[i*2 + 1].get_xdata()[1]]

    # gets y coordinates for the whisker at the bottom
    whisker_y_min = whiskers[i*2].get_ydata()[1]
    
    # gets y coordinates for the whisker at the top
    whisker_y_max = whiskers[i*2 + 1].get_ydata()[1]
    
    # to position labels
    label_x = x.mean()
    label_y_min = whisker_y_min
    label_y_max = whisker_y_max
    
    # Add the labels
    plt.text(label_x, label_y_min, f'Min: {label_y_min:.0f}', ha='center', va='bottom')
    plt.text(label_x, label_y_max, f'Max: {label_y_max:.0f}', ha='center', va='top')

plt.show()

This is a boxplot showing the spread of median rent of 4 room flats in three towns, Bedok, Serangoon and Jurong East. The minimum and maximum for each boxplot has been labelled.

The minimum median rental price in Bedok is 800SGD, while the maximum is 3000SGD. The minimum median rental price in Serangoon is 800SGD, while the maximum is 3200SGD. The minimum median rental price in Jurong East is 750SGD, while the maximum is 3100SGD. The difference between the minimum and maximum median rental price for each of these towns is 2200SGD, 2400SGD and 2350SGD respectively.

Jurong East shows a wider interquartile range (IQR) compared to Serangoon and Bedok, indicating a greater variability in rent prices. Serangoon and Bedok have similar IQRs, suggesting relatively consistent rent prices within those towns.

It is important to consider additional factors such as facilities when looking at median rent values.

This figure illustrates the trend between quarters in different years and the median rental price for 4-room flats in Serangoon. It consists of two line graphs: the top graph displays the uncleaned data, while the bottom graph showcases the accurate data.

Examining the first line graph, we observe an inconsistency in the dataset. In 2005-Q3, the median rental price is depicted as 1000 SGD, but it abruptly drops to 0 SGD in the subsequent quarter, indicating an error. Consequently, the dataset underwent a simple cleaning process to ensure the accuracy of the data analysis.

The second line graph provides a more reliable representation. It demonstrates the trend between quarters within a year and the corresponding median rental price. Over the years, there is a consistent increase in the median rental price. From 2005-Q2 to 2006-Q4, the median rental price remained relatively stable at around 1000 SGD. Subsequently, it climbed to approximately 2000 SGD in 2008-Q2. Gradually, the median rental price continued its ascent, surpassing 2500 SGD in 2012-Q3, where it plateaued until 2015-Q2. Following that, it experienced a slight decline, hovering around 2250 SGD until 2022-Q2. Subsequently, in 2022-Q4, there was a sharp surge, propelling the median rental price above 3000 SGD.

The primary factor contributing to the upward trajectory of the median rental price over time is the availability of educational and healthcare facilities in the vicinity. As these facilities expand, they enhance accessibility, thereby increasing the median rental price for flats in the area.

Considering the current trend of increasing median rental prices, opting to rent a 4-room flat in Serangoon appears to be a good decision.

How many different type of schools are in Serangoon, and what are they?¶

In [ ]:
# Extract the schools in serangoon area
serangoon = data_school_info[data_school_info['dgp_code'] == 'SERANGOON']

#get school names
school_names = np.unique(serangoon['school_name'])

# get the main level code for each school (primary,secondary,jc)
main_level= np.unique(serangoon['mainlevel_code'])

# get the number of schools for each main level code
num_schools = []
for main in main_level:
    num_schools.append(len(serangoon[serangoon['mainlevel_code'] == main]))

# Create the stacked bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))

# used to track the bottom position of each bar
bottom = np.zeros(len(main_level))

# loop each school name
for school_name in school_names:

    # filter dataset for current sch
    school_data = serangoon[serangoon['school_name'] == school_name]
    # store the counts for school type
    counts = []
    for code in main_level:
        # filter dataset for current type code and get its count
        count = len(school_data[school_data['mainlevel_code'] == code])
        counts.append(count)
    plt.bar(main_level, counts, bottom=bottom, label=school_name)
    bottom += counts

plt.xlabel('Type Code',fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Number of Schools',fontsize=15)
plt.ylim(0,6)
plt.title('Schools in Serangoon by Type Code',fontsize=20)
plt.grid(color="gray",alpha=0.7)
plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
plt.show()

This is an informative bar chart depicting the distribution of schools in Serangoon based on their types, namely Junior College, Primary School, and Secondary School. The Serangoon area hosts a total of three types of schools.

Specifically, Nanyang Junior College represents the sole Junior College in Serangoon. As for Primary Schools, there are five options available: CHIJ Our Lady of Good Counsel, Rosyth School, St. Gabriel's Primary School, Yangzheng Primary School, and Zhonghua Primary School. Additionally, Serangoon is home to four Secondary Schools, namely Peicai Secondary School, Serangoon Garden Secondary School, St. Gabriel's Secondary School, and Zhonghua Secondary School.

Although Serangoon may not boast the highest or lowest property prices in Singapore, this insightful bar chart showcases the abundance of educational institutions available within the area. Therefore, prospective property buyers with children are encouraged to consider Serangoon as an ideal location, offering a diverse range of school options.
